In the following decades, several breakthroughs paved the way for the broad application of the FDTD method (for a detailed treatment, the reader is referred to the text books of Kunz and Leubbers [23] and Taflove and Hagness [24]):

•
complete understanding of the numerical properties like stability, accuracy, dispersion, and gridding effects [25]–

[28];

•
development of absorbing boundary conditions culminating in the PML and the uniaxial PML [2], [29], [30];

•
adaption to radiation and scattering problems with the total field/scattered field formalism, plane-wave sources, and near-to-far-field transformation [31]–
[33];

•
adaption to microwave engineering problems with appropriate waveguide sources, lumped elements, and extraction of network parameters [34], [35];

•
coupling with thermal solvers, circuit simulators, and semiconductor device solvers [36]–
[38];

•
modeling of dispersive material properties using auxiliary differential equations and recursive convolution methods [39], [40];

•
efficient treatment of oblique, very thin, or very small features using subgrids, subcell models, or surface impedance concepts [41], [42];

•
generalization of the Yee grid to nonorthogonal unstructured grids, and adaption to periodic or axial symmetric bodies [43], [44].

